# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-switching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] A **collision domain** is a network segment (connected by a shared medium or through repeaters) where simultaneous data transmissions collide with one another as a result of more than one device attempting to send a packet on the network segment at the same time.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] The collision domain applies particularly in wireless networks, but also affected early versions of Ethernet.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Members of a collision domain may be involved in collisions with one another.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Devices outside the collision domain do not have collisions with those inside.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] A channel access method dictates that only one device in the collision domain may transmit at any one time, and the other devices in the domain listen to the network and refrain from transmitting while others are already transmitting in order to avoid collisions.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Because only one device may be transmitting at any one time, total network bandwidth is shared among all devices on the collision domain.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Collisions also decrease network efficiency in a collision domain as collisions require devices to abort transmission and retransmit at a later time.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Since data bits are propagated at a finite speed, *simultaneously* is to be defined in terms of the size of the collision domain and the minimum packet size allowed.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] A smaller packet size or a larger dimension would make it possible for a sender to finish sending the packet without the first bits of the message being able to reach the most remote node.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] So, that node could start sending as well, without a clue to the transmission already taking place and destroying the first packet.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Unless the size of the collision domain allows the initial sender to receive the second transmission attempt – the collision – within the time it takes to send the packet, they would neither be able to detect the collision nor to repeat the transmission – this is called a late collision.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] On Ethernet using shared media, collisions are resolved using carrier-sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD) in which the competing packets are discarded and re-sent one at a time.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] This becomes a source of inefficiency in the network.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Early Ethernet variants (10BASE5, 10BASE2) were based on a shared wire and inherently half-duplex, representing a single, potentially large collision domain.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Collision domains are also found in an Ethernet hub or repeater environment where each host segment connects to a hub, and all segments represent only one collision domain within one broadcast domain.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Collision domains are also found in other shared medium networks, e. g. wireless networks such as Wi-Fi.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Modern wired networks use a network switch to reduce or eliminate collisions.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] By connecting each device directly to a port on the switch, either each port on a switch becomes its own collision domain (in the case of half-duplex links), or the possibility of collisions is eliminated in the case of full-duplex links.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] For Gigabit Ethernet and faster, no hubs or repeaters exist and all devices require full-duplex links.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Most wireless LAN networks use the carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA) method.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] In addition to the requirements of a shared wire medium, wireless networks add the hidden node problem where two senders can't hear each other's transmissions, but they cause a collision at the receiver between them.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Multiple Access with Collision Avoidance for Wireless is one such approach used, specifically in 802.11 RTS/CTS.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Central coordination is another means of solving this problem for a collision domain.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] This technique is employed by Wireless Multimedia Extensions.
[src:network-switching/collision-domain] Point coordination function and distributed coordination function are specific implementations.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Compared to store and forward, this technique reduces latency through the switch and relies on the destination devices for error handling.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Pure cut-through switching is only possible when the speed of the outgoing interface is at least equal or higher than the incoming interface speed.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Adaptive switching dynamically selects between cut-through and store and forward behaviors based on current network conditions.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Cut-through switching is closely associated with wormhole switching.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] When cut-through switching is used in Ethernet the switch is not able to verify the integrity of an incoming frame before forwarding it.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] The technology was developed by Kalpana, the company that introduced the first Ethernet switch.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] The primary advantage of cut-through Ethernet switches, compared to store-and-forward Ethernet switches, is lower latency.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Cut-through Ethernet switches can support an end-to-end network delay latency of about ten microseconds.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] End-to-end application latencies below 3 microseconds require specialized hardware such as InfiniBand.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] A cut-through switch will forward corrupted frames, whereas a store and forward switch will drop them.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] **Fragment free** is a variation on cut-through switching that partially addresses this problem by assuring that collision fragments are not forwarded.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Fragment free will hold the frame until the first 64 bytes are read from the source to detect a collision before forwarding.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] This is only useful if there is a chance of a collision on the source port.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] The theory here is that frames that are damaged by collisions are often shorter than the minimum valid Ethernet frame size of 64 bytes.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] With a fragment-free buffer, the first 64 bytes of each frame update the source MAC and port if necessary, provide the destination MAC, and allow forwarding the frame.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] If the frame is less than 64 bytes, it is discarded.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Frames that are smaller than 64 bytes are called runts; this is why fragment-free switching is sometimes called "runt-less" switching.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Because the switch only ever buffers 64 bytes of each frame, fragment-free is a faster mode than store-and-forward, but there still exists a risk of forwarding bad frames.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Cut-through switching is the dominant switching architecture in Fibre Channel due to the low-latency performance required for SCSI traffic.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Brocade has implemented cut-through switching in its Fibre Channel ASICs since the 1990s and has been implemented in tens of millions of ports in production SANs worldwide.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] CRC errors are detected in a cut-through switch and indicated by marking the corrupted frame EOF field as "invalid".
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] The destination devices (host or storage) sees the invalid EOF and discards the frame prior to sending it to the application or LUN.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Discarding corrupted frames by the destination device is a 100% reliable method for error handling and is mandated by Fibre Channel standards driven by Technical Committee T11.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Discarding corrupted frames at the destination device also minimizes the time to recover bad frames.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] As soon as the destination device receives the EOF marker as "invalid", recovery of the corrupted frame can begin.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] With store and forward, the corrupted frame is discarded at the switch forcing a SCSI timeout and a SCSI retry for recovery that can result in delays of tens of seconds.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Cut-through switching was one of the important features of IP networks using ATM networks since the edge routers of the ATM network were able to use cell switching through the core of the network with low latency at all points.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] With higher speed links, this has become less of a problem since packet latency has become much smaller.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Cut-through switching is very popular in InfiniBand networks, since these are often deployed in environments where latency is a prime concern, such as supercomputer clusters.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] A closely allied concept is offered by the Exim mail transfer agent.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] When operating as a forwarder the onward connection can be made to the destination while the source connection is still open.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] This permits data-time rejection (due, for example, to content-scanning) by the target MTA to be notified to the source MTA within the SMTP connection, rather than the traditional bounce message necessitated by the more usual store-and-forward operation.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Cut-through switching has been applied to make block-relay lower latency in Bitcoin.
[src:network-switching/cut-through-switching] Low latency is critical for Bitcoin miners to reduce the rate at which their blocks are orphaned.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] A **frame** is a digital data transmission unit in computer networking and telecommunications.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] In packet switched systems, a frame is a simple container for a single network packet.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] In other telecommunications systems, a frame is a repeating structure supporting time-division multiplexing.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] A frame typically includes frame synchronization features consisting of a sequence of bits or symbols that indicate to the receiver the beginning and end of the payload data within the stream of symbols or bits it receives.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] If a receiver is connected to the system during frame transmission, it ignores the data until it detects a new frame synchronization sequence.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] In the OSI model of computer networking, a frame is the protocol data unit at the data link layer.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] Frames are the result of the final layer of encapsulation before the data is transmitted over the physical layer.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] A frame is "the unit of transmission in a link layer protocol, and consists of a link layer header followed by a packet." Each frame is separated from the next by an interframe gap.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] A frame is a series of bits generally composed of frame synchronization bits, the packet payload, and a frame check sequence.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] Examples are Ethernet frames, Wi-Fi frames, 4G frames, Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) frames, Fibre Channel frames, and V.42 modem frames.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] Often, frames of several different sizes are nested inside each other.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] In telecommunications, specifically in time-division multiplex (TDM) and time-division multiple access (TDMA) variants, a frame is a cyclically repeated data block that consists of a fixed number of time slots, one for each logical TDM channel or TDMA transmitter.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] In this context, a frame is typically an entity at the physical layer.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] TDM application examples are SONET/SDH and the ISDN circuit-switched B-channel, while TDMA examples are Circuit Switched Data used in early cellular voice services.
[src:network-switching/frame-networking] The frame is also an entity for time-division duplex, where the mobile terminal may transmit during some time slots and receive during others.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A **network switch** (also called **switching hub**, **bridging hub**, **Ethernet switch**, and—by the IEEE—**MAC bridge**) is networking hardware that connects devices on a computer network by using packet switching to receive and forward data to the destination device.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A network switch is a multiport network bridge that uses MAC addresses to forward data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Some switches can also forward data at the network layer (layer 3) by additionally incorporating routing functionality.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Such switches are commonly known as layer-3 switches or multilayer switches.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Switches for Ethernet are the most common form of network switch.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] The first MAC Bridge was invented in 1983 by Mark Kempf, an engineer in the Networking Advanced Development group of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:network-switching/network-switch] The first two-port bridge product (LANBridge 100) was introduced by that company shortly after.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] The company subsequently produced multi-port switches for both Ethernet and FDDI.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] DEC decided to license its MAC Bridge patent on a royalty-free, non-discriminatory basis that allowed IEEE standardization.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] This permitted a number of other companies to produce multi-port switches, including Kalpana.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Ethernet was initially a shared-access medium, but the introduction of the MAC bridge began its transformation into its most-common point-to-point form without a collision domain.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Switches also exist for other types of networks, including Fibre Channel, Asynchronous Transfer Mode, and InfiniBand.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Unlike repeater hubs, which broadcast the same data out of each port and let the devices pick out the data addressed to them, a network switch learns the Ethernet addresses of connected devices and then only forwards data to the port connected to the device to which it is addressed.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A switch is a device in a computer network that connects other devices together.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Multiple data cables are plugged into a switch to enable communication between different networked devices.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Switches manage the flow of data across a network by transmitting a received network packet only to the one or more devices for which the packet is intended.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Each networked device connected to a switch can be identified by its network address, allowing the switch to direct the flow of traffic, maximizing the security and efficiency of the network.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A switch is more intelligent than an Ethernet hub, which simply retransmits packets out of every port of the hub except the port on which the packet was received, unable to distinguish different recipients, and achieves an overall lower network efficiency.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] An Ethernet switch operates at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to create a separate collision domain for each switch port.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Each device connected to a switch port can transfer data to any of the other ports at any time and the transmissions will not interfere.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Because broadcasts are still being forwarded to all connected devices by the switch, the newly formed network segment continues to be a broadcast domain.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Switches may also operate at higher layers of the OSI model, including the network layer and above.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A switch that also operates at these higher layers is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Segmentation involves the use of a switch to split a larger collision domain into smaller ones in order to reduce collision probability and to improve overall network throughput.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In the extreme case (i.e., micro-segmentation), each device is directly connected to a switch port dedicated to the device.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In contrast to an Ethernet hub, there is a separate collision domain on each switch port.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] This allows computers to have dedicated bandwidth on point-to-point connections to the network and also to run in full-duplex mode.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Full-duplex mode has only one transmitter and one receiver per collision domain, making collisions impossible.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] The network switch plays an integral role in most modern Ethernet local area networks (LANs).
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Mid-to-large-sized LANs contain a number of linked managed switches.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Small office/home office (SOHO) applications typically use a single switch, or an all-purpose device such as a residential gateway to access small office/home broadband services such as DSL or cable Internet.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In most of these cases, the end-user device contains a router and components that interface to the particular physical broadband technology.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Many switches have pluggable modules, such as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) modules.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] These modules often contain a transceiver that connects the switch to a physical medium, such as a fiber optic cable.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Alternatively, DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cables may be used in place of modules.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] These modules were preceded by Medium Attachment Units connected via Attachment Unit Interfaces to switches and have evolved over time: the first modules were Gigabit interface converters, followed by XENPAK modules, SFP modules, XFP transceivers, SFP+ modules, QSFP, QSFP-DD, and OSFP modules.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Pluggable modules are also used for transmitting video in broadcast applications.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] CPO is also considerably easier to adapt to water cooling.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Switches are most commonly used as the network connection point for hosts at the edge of a network.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In the hierarchical internetworking model and similar network architectures, switches are also used deeper in the network to provide connections between the switches at the edge.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In switches intended for commercial use, built-in or modular interfaces make it possible to connect different types of networks, including Ethernet, Fibre Channel, RapidIO, ATM, ITU-T G.hn and 802.11.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] This connectivity can be at any of the layers mentioned.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] While the layer-2 functionality is adequate for bandwidth-shifting within one technology, interconnecting technologies such as Ethernet and Token Ring is performed more easily at layer 3 or via routing.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Devices that interconnect at the layer 3 are traditionally called routers.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Where there is a need for a great deal of analysis of network performance and security, switches may be connected between WAN routers as places for analytic modules.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Some vendors provide firewall, network intrusion detection, and performance analysis modules that can plug into switch ports.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Some of these functions may be on combined modules.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Through port mirroring, a switch can create a mirror image of data that can go to an external device, such as intrusion detection systems and packet sniffers.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A modern switch may implement power over Ethernet (PoE), which avoids the need for attached devices, such as a VoIP phone or wireless access point, to have a separate power supply.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Because switches can have their power circuits connected to uninterruptible power supplies, the connected device can continue operating even when regular office power fails.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In 1989 and 1990, Kalpana introduced the first multiport Ethernet switch, its seven-port EtherSwitch.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Modern commercial switches primarily use Ethernet interfaces.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] The core function of an Ethernet switch is to provide multiple ports of layer-2 bridging.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Layer-1 functionality is required in all switches in support of the higher layers.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Many switches also perform operations at other layers.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A device capable of more than bridging is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A layer 2 network device is a multiport device that uses hardware addresses (MAC addresses) to process and forward data at the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:network-switching/network-switch] A switch operating as a network bridge may interconnect otherwise separate layer 2 networks.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] The bridge learns the MAC address of each connected device, storing this data in a table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] This table is often implemented using high-speed content-addressable memory (CAM), some vendors refer to the MAC address table as a CAM table.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Bridges also buffer an incoming packet and adapt the transmission speed to that of the outgoing port.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] While there are specialized applications, such as storage area networks, where the input and output interfaces are the same bandwidth, this is not always the case in general LAN applications.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In LANs, a switch used for end-user access typically concentrates lower bandwidth and uplinks into a higher bandwidth.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] The Ethernet header at the start of the frame contains all the information required to make a forwarding decision; some high-performance switches can begin forwarding the frame to the destination whilst still receiving the frame payload from the sender.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] This cut-through switching can significantly reduce latency through the switch.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Interconnects between switches may be regulated using the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) that disables forwarding on links so that the resulting local area network is a tree without switching loops.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] In contrast to routers, spanning tree bridges must have topologies with only one active path between two points.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Shortest path bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) are layer 2 alternatives to STP, which allow all paths to be active with multiple equal cost paths.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Rack-mounted switches may be stand-alone units, stackable switches or large chassis units with swappable line cards.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] It is difficult to monitor traffic that is bridged using a switch because only the sending and receiving ports can see the traffic.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] These monitoring features are rarely present on consumer-grade switches.
[src:network-switching/network-switch] Other monitoring methods include connecting a layer-1 hub or network tap between the monitored device and its switch port.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In telecommunications, **packet switching** is a method of grouping data into short messages in fixed format, i.e., *packets,* that are transmitted over a telecommunications network.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packets consist of a header and a payload.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The header directs the packet to its destination, where the payload is extracted and used by an operating system, application software, or higher-layer protocols.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching is the primary basis for data communications in computer networks worldwide.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] During the early 1960s, American engineer Paul Baran developed a concept he called *distributed adaptive message block switching* as part of a research program at the RAND Corporation, funded by the United States Department of Defense.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] His proposal was to provide a fault-tolerant, efficient method for communication of voice messages using low-cost hardware to route the message blocks across a distributed network.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] His ideas contradicted then-established principles of pre-allocation of network bandwidth, exemplified by the development of telecommunications in the Bell System.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The new concept found little resonance among network implementers until the independent work of British computer scientist Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory beginning in 1965.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Davies developed the concept for data communication using software switches in a high-speed computer network and coined the term *packet switching*.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] His work inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following, including the incorporation of the concept into the design of the ARPANET in the United States and the CYCLADES network in France.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The ARPANET and CYCLADES were the primary precursor networks of the modern Internet.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching allows delivery of variable bit rate data streams, realized as sequences of short messages in fixed format, i.e.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] *packets*, over a computer network which allocates transmission resources as needed using statistical multiplexing or dynamic bandwidth allocation techniques.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] As they traverse networking hardware, such as switches and routers, packets are received, buffered, queued, and retransmitted (stored and forwarded), resulting in variable latency and throughput depending on link capacity and traffic load on the network.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet-based communication may be implemented with or without intermediate forwarding nodes (switches and routers).
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In case of a shared physical medium (such as radio or 10BASE5), the packets may be delivered according to a multiple access scheme.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching contrasts with another principal networking paradigm, circuit switching, a method which pre-allocates dedicated network bandwidth specifically for each communication session, each having a constant bit rate and latency between nodes.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] A packet switch has four components: input ports, output ports, routing processor, and switching fabric.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The concept of switching small blocks of data was invented independently by Paul Baran at the RAND Corporation during the early 1960s in the US and Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory (NPL) in the UK in 1965.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In the late 1950s, the US Air Force established a wide area network for the Semi-Automatic Ground Environment (SAGE) radar defense system.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Recognizing vulnerabilities in this network, the Air Force sought a system that might survive a nuclear attack to enable a response, thus diminishing the attractiveness of the first strike advantage by enemies (see Mutual assured destruction).
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In the early 1960s, Baran invented the concept of *distributed adaptive message block switching* in support of the Air Force initiative.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The concept was first presented to the Air Force in the summer of 1961 as briefing B-265, later published as RAND report P-2626 in 1962, and finally in report RM 3420 in 1964.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The reports describe a general architecture for a large-scale, distributed, survivable communications network.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The proposal was composed of three key ideas: use of a decentralized network with multiple paths between any two points; dividing user messages into *message blocks;* and delivery of these messages by store and forward switching.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Baran's network design was focused on high-speed digital communication of voice messages using hardware switches that were low-cost electronics.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Christopher Strachey, who became Oxford University's first Professor of Computation, filed a patent application in the United Kingdom for time-sharing in February 1959.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In June that year, he gave a paper "Time Sharing in Large Fast Computers" at the UNESCO Information Processing Conference in Paris where he passed the concept on to J.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Licklider (along with John McCarthy) was instrumental in the development of time-sharing.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] After conversations with Licklider about time-sharing with remote computers in 1965, Davies independently invented a similar data communication concept.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] His insight was to use short messages in fixed format with high data transmission rates to achieve rapid communications.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] He went on to develop a design for a hierarchical, high-speed computer network including interface computers and communication protocols.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] He coined the term *packet switching*, and proposed building a commercial nationwide data network in the UK.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] He gave a talk on the proposal in 1966, after which a person from the Ministry of Defence (MoD) told him about Baran's work.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Roger Scantlebury, a member of Davies' team, presented their work (and referenced that of Baran) at the October 1967 Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP).
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] At the conference, Scantlebury proposed packet switching for use in the ARPANET and persuaded Larry Roberts the economics were favorable to message switching.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Davies had chosen some of the same parameters for his original network design as did Baran, such as a packet size of 1024 bits.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Davies proposed that a local-area network should be built at the laboratory to serve the needs of NPL and prove the feasibility of packet switching.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] After a pilot experiment in early 1969, the NPL Data Communications Network began service in 1970.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Davies was invited to Japan to give a series of lectures on packet switching.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The NPL team carried out simulation work on datagrams and congestion in networks on a scale to provide data communication across the United Kingdom.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Larry Roberts made the key decisions in the request for proposal to build the ARPANET.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Roberts met Baran in February 1967, but did not discuss networks.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Roberts was known for making decisions quickly.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Immediately after SOSP, he incorporated Davies' concepts and designs for packet switching to enable the data communications on the network, and sought input from Baran.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] A contemporary of Roberts' from MIT, Leonard Kleinrock had researched the application of queueing theory in the field of message switching for his doctoral dissertation in 1961–62 and published it as a book in 1964.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Davies, in his 1966 paper on packet switching, applied Kleinrock's techniques to show that "there is an ample margin between the estimated performance of the [packet-switched] system and the stated requirement" in terms of a satisfactory response time for a human user.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] This addressed a key question about the viability of computer networking.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Larry Roberts brought Kleinrock into the ARPANET project informally in early 1967.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Roberts and Taylor recognized the issue of response time was important, but did not apply Kleinrock's methods to assess this and based their design on a store-and-forward system that was not intended for real-time computing.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] After SOSP, and after Roberts' direction to use packet switching, Kleinrock sought input from Baran and proposed to retain Baran and RAND as advisors.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The ARPANET working group assigned Kleinrock responsibility to prepare a report on software for the IMP.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In 1968, Roberts awarded Kleinrock a contract to establish a Network Measurement Center (NMC) at UCLA to measure and model the performance of packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Bolt Beranek & Newman (BBN) won the contract to build the network.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Designed principally by Bob Kahn, it was the first wide-area packet-switched network with distributed control.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The BBN "IMP Guys" independently developed significant aspects of the network's internal operation, including the routing algorithm, flow control, software design, and network control.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The UCLA NMC and the BBN team also investigated network congestion.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The Network Working Group, led by Steve Crocker, a graduate student of Kleinrock's at UCLA, developed the host-to-host protocol, the Network Control Program, which was approved by Barry Wessler for ARPA, after he ordered certain more exotic elements to be dropped.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In 1970, Kleinrock extended his earlier analytic work on message switching to packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The ARPANET was demonstrated at the International Conference on Computer Communication (ICCC) in Washington in October 1972.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] However, fundamental questions about the design of packet-switched networks remained.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Roberts presented the idea of packet switching to communication industry professionals in the early 1970s.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Before ARPANET was operating, they argued that the router buffers would quickly run out.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] After the ARPANET was operating, they argued that packet switching would never be economic without the government subsidy.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Baran had faced the same rejection and thus failed to convince the military to construct a packet switching network in the 1960s.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The CYCLADES network was designed by Louis Pouzin in the early 1970s to study internetworking.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] It was the first to implement the end-to-end principle of Davies, and make the host computers responsible for the reliable delivery of data on a packet-switched network, rather than this being a service of the network itself.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] His team was thus first to tackle the highly-complex problem of providing user applications with a reliable virtual circuit service while using a best-effort service, an early contribution to what will be the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Bob Metcalfe and others at Xerox PARC outlined the idea of Ethernet and the PARC Universal Packet (PUP) for internetworking.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In May 1974, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn described the Transmission Control Program, an internetworking protocol for sharing resources using packet-switching among the nodes.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The specifications of the TCP were then published in RFC 675 (*Specification of Internet Transmission Control Program*), written by Vint Cerf, Yogen Dalal and Carl Sunshine in December 1974.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The X.25 protocol, developed by Rémi Després and others, was built on the concept of virtual circuits.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In the mid-late 1970s and early 1980s, national and international public data networks emerged using X.25 which was developed with participation from France, the UK, Japan, USA and Canada.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] It was complemented with X.75 to enable internetworking.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In the late 1970s, the monolithic Transmission Control Program was layered as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), atop the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers developed this into the Internet protocol suite and the associated Internet architecture and governance that emerged in the 1980s.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Leonard Kleinrock carried out theoretical work at UCLA during the 1970s analyzing throughput and delay in the ARPANET.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Kleinrock published hundreds of research papers, which ultimately launched a new field of research on the theory and application of queuing theory to computer networks.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] His work on hierarchical routing with student Farouk Kamoun became critical to the operation of the Internet.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching was shown to be optimal in the Huffman coding sense in 1978.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] For a period in the 1980s and early 1990s, the network engineering community was polarized over the implementation of competing protocol suites, commonly known as the Protocol Wars.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] It was unclear which of the Internet protocol suite and the OSI model would result in the best and most robust computer networks.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) VLSI (very-large-scale integration) technology led to the development of high-speed broadband packet switching during the 1980s–1990s.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In the 1978 special edition of the Proceedings of the IEEE on packet switching, Bob Kahn, the guest editor, wrote that "analysis has had little direct impact on the network design problem".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In Roberts' paper on "Packet Switching Economics" for the L.M.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Ericsson prize for research in data communications in 1982, he referenced only Davies' 1967 paper for SOSP, not the work of Baran or Kleinrock.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Kleinrock's paper for the same prize was titled "Packet Switching Principles".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In Roberts' 1986 conference paper on "The ARPANET & Computer Networks", he also cites Baran's 1964 paper and one of his own papers from 1966; but only references Kleinrock's work from the 1970s, which addressed the ARPANET.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] This paper was republished on the web by Roberts in 1995.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In 1997, along with seven other Internet pioneers, Roberts and Kleinrock co-wrote "Brief History of the Internet" published by the Internet Society.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In it, Kleinrock is described as having "published the first paper on packet switching theory in July 1961 and the first book on the subject in 1964".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Many sources about the history of the Internet began to reflect these claims as uncontroversial facts.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] This became the subject of what Katie Hafner called a "paternity dispute" in The New York Times in 2001.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The disagreement about Kleinrock's contribution to packet switching escalated after a statement made on Kleinrock's profile on the UCLA Computer Science department website sometime in the 1990s.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Here, he was referred to as the "Inventor of the Internet Technology".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The webpage's depictions of Kleinrock's achievements provoked anger among some early Internet pioneers.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The dispute over priority became a public issue after Donald Davies posthumously published a paper in 2001 in which he denied that Kleinrock's work in the early 1960s was related to packet switching, stating "I can find no evidence that he understood the principles of packet switching".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Davies also described ARPANET project manager Larry Roberts as supporting Kleinrock, referring to Roberts' writings online and Kleinrock's UCLA webpage profile as "very misleading".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson wrote that Kleinrock's claims "led to an outcry among many of the other Internet pioneers, who publicly attacked Kleinrock and said that his brief mention of breaking messages into smaller pieces did not come close to being a proposal for packet switching".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Davies' paper reignited a previous dispute over who deserves credit for getting the ARPANET online between engineers at Bolt, Beranek, and Newman (BBN) who had been involved in building and designing the ARPANET IMP on the one side, and ARPA-related researchers on the other.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] This earlier dispute is exemplified by BBN's Will Crowther, who in a 1990 oral history described Paul Baran's packet switching design (which he called hot-potato routing), as "crazy" and non-sensical, despite the ARPA team having advocated for it.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Former IPTO director Bob Taylor also joined the debate, stating that "authors who have interviewed dozens of Arpanet pioneers know very well that the Kleinrock-Roberts claims are not believed".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson notes that "until the mid-1990s Kleinrock had credited [Baran and Davies] with coming up with the idea of packet switching".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] A subsequent version of Kleinrock's biography webpage was copyrighted in 2009 by Kleinrock.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] He was called on to defend his position over subsequent decades.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] A paper published in the journal *Internet Histories* in 2019 supported Kleinrock's view; the author interviewed Kleinrock and Roberts, and did not interview Scantlebury.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In 2023, Kleinrock acknowledged that his work published in the early 1960s was about message switching and claimed he was thinking about packet switching.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Primary sources and historians recognize Baran and Davies for independently inventing the concept of digital packet switching used in modern computer networking including the ARPANET and the Internet.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Kleinrock has received many awards for his ground-breaking applied mathematical research on packet switching, carried out in the 1970s, which was an extension of his pioneering work in the early 1960s on the optimization of message delays in communication networks.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Russell said "'Internet history' also suffers from a ... methodological, problem: it tends to be too close to its sources.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers are alive, active, and eager to shape the histories that describe their accomplishments.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Many museums and historians are equally eager to interview the pioneers and to publicize their stories".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching may be classified into connectionless packet switching, using datagrams, and connection-oriented packet switching, using virtual circuits.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Examples of connectionless systems are Ethernet, IP, and the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Connection-oriented systems include X.25, Frame Relay, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), and TCP.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In connectionless mode, each packet is labeled with a destination address, source address, and port numbers.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] It may also be labeled with the sequence number of the packet.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] This information eliminates the need for a pre-established path to help the packet find its way to its destination, but means that more information is needed in the packet header, which is therefore larger.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The packets are routed individually, sometimes taking different paths, resulting in out-of-order delivery.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] At the destination, the original message may be reassembled in the correct order, based on the packet sequence numbers.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Thus, a virtual circuit carrying a byte stream is provided to the application by a transport layer protocol, although the network only provides a connectionless network layer service.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transmission requires a setup phase to establish the parameters of communication before any packet is transferred.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The signaling protocols used for setup allow the application to specify its requirements and discover link parameters.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Acceptable values for service parameters may be negotiated.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The packets transferred may include a connection identifier rather than address information and the packet header can be smaller, as it only needs to contain this code and any information, such as length, timestamp, or sequence number, which is different for different packets.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In this case, address information is only transferred to each node during the connection setup phase, when the route to the destination is discovered and an entry is added to the switching table in each network node through which the connection passes.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] When a connection identifier is used, routing a packet requires the node to look up the connection identifier in a table.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transport layer protocols such as TCP provide a connection-oriented service by using an underlying connectionless network.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In this case, the end-to-end principle dictates that the end nodes, not the network itself, are responsible for the connection-oriented behavior.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In telecommunication networks, packet switching is used to optimize the usage of channel capacity and increase robustness.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Compared to circuit switching, packet switching is highly dynamic, allocating channel capacity based on usage instead of explicit reservations.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] This can reduce wasted capacity caused by underutilized reservations at the cost of removing bandwidth guarantees.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] In practice, congestion control is generally used in IP networks to dynamically negotiate capacity between connections.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching may also increase the robustness of networks in the face of failures.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] If a node fails, connections do not need to be interrupted, as packets may be routed around the failure.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching is used in the Internet and most local area networks.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The Internet is implemented by the Internet Protocol Suite using a variety of link layer technologies.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] For example, Ethernet and Frame Relay are common.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Newer mobile phone technologies (e.g., GSM, LTE) also use packet switching.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Packet switching is associated with connectionless networking because, in these systems, no connection agreement needs to be established between communicating parties prior to exchanging data.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] X.25, the international CCITT standard of 1976, is a notable use of packet switching in that it provides to users a service of flow-controlled virtual circuits.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] These virtual circuits reliably carry variable-length packets with data order preservation.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] DATAPAC in Canada was the first public network to support X.25, followed by TRANSPAC in France.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) is another virtual circuit technology.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] It differs from X.25 in that it uses small fixed-length packets (cells), and that the network imposes no flow control to users.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Technologies such as MPLS and the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) create virtual circuits on top of datagram networks.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] MPLS and its predecessors, as well as ATM, have been called "fast packet" technologies.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] MPLS, indeed, has been called "ATM without cells".
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] Virtual circuits are especially useful in building robust failover mechanisms and allocating bandwidth for delay-sensitive applications.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] The work of Donald Davies in the late 1960s on data communication and computer network design became well known in the United States, Europe and Japan.
[src:network-switching/packet-switching] This was the "cornerstone" that inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] Store-and-forward switching centers are usually implemented in mobile service stations, where the messages that are sent from the sender are first sent to these centers.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] If the destination address isn't available, then the center stores this message and tries sending it later.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] This improves the probability of the message being delivered.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] In the other case, if the destination is available at that time, then the message is immediately sent.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] Store-and-forward networks predate the use of computers.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] Point-to-point teleprinter equipment was used to send messages, which were stored at the receiving end on punched paper tape at a relay center.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] A human operator at the center removed the message tape from the receiving machine, read the addressing information, and then sent it toward its destination on the appropriate outbound point-to-point teleprinter link.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] If the outbound link was in use, the operator placed the message in tape in a physical queue, usually consisting of a set of clips or hooks.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] A major relay center in the mid-1900s might have dozens of inbound and outbound teleprinters, scores of operators, and thousands of messages in the queues during peak periods.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] Operators referred to these centers as "torn-tape relay centers", a reference to removing the received message from the inbound teleprinter by tearing the paper tape to separate one message from the next.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] The U.S. military term for such a center was "Non-Automated Relay Center" (NARC).
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] In 1948, Western Union introduced Plan 55-A, the first automatic electromechanical store-and-forward message switching system.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] All message storage was performed by paper tape punches paired with paper tape readers, with a bin in between.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] It is very common for an email system using SMTP to accept a message, store it and then forward it on elsewhere.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] Although fully open mail relays are no longer common, not only does simple server-based forwarding work this way, but also many email filtering and automated electronic mailing lists services.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] SMS messages are first sent to a Short Message service center where they are stored temporarily before being forwarded to the intended recipient's phone, even if they are not currently reachable, allowing for delivery later when they come back online.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] Prior to the deployment of the Internet, computers were connected via a variety of point-to-point techniques, with many smaller computers using dial-up connections.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] The UUCP store-and-forward protocols allowed a message (typically e-mail) to move across the collection of computers and eventually reach its destination.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] Late in the 20th century, store-and-forward techniques evolved into packet switching, which replaced them for most purposes.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] FidoNet was an email store-and-forward system for bulletin board systems that peaked at 45,000 systems with millions of users across the world.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] The system was highly efficient, using the latest file compression and file transfer systems to aggressively drive down the cost of transmission on what was largely a hobby network.
[src:network-switching/store-and-forward] The system was later modified to support public messages (forums) called EchoMail, which grew to about 8 MB a day, compressed.
